events.title: Birth
events.summary: Johann Sebastian Bach was born in Eisenach, Germany, as the youngest child of Johann Ambrosius Bach, the director of town musicians. His early exposure to music came from his father and numerous musician uncles.
events.fun_version: Johann Sebastian Bach was born in Eisenach, Germany, as the youngest child of Johann Ambrosius Bach, the director of town musicians. He learned music the same way kids learn to eat vegetables: by being forced to listen to his dad and a bunch of uncles playing stringed instruments until he couldn’t hear a thing!

events.title: Mother's Death
events.summary: Bach's mother died in 1694, followed by the death of his father shortly after, leading him to live with his eldest brother who was an organist.
events.fun_version: Imagine a young Bach, losing both parents and ending up with his oldest brother, who was an organist.

events.title: Move to Ohrdruf
events.summary: After the death of his parents, Bach moved to Ohrdruf to live with his eldest brother, Johann Christoph Bach, where he studied and copied music, despite restrictions.
events.fun_version: After the overly dramatic twist of losing his parents, Bach packed his bags and moved into his eldest brother's place in Ohrdruf. There, with a music stand as his loyal sidekick, he dove headfirst into copying music like a kid in a candy store, all while juggling a few house rules that could rival a royal decree!

events.title: Enrollment in St. Michael's School
events.summary: Bach enrolled in the prestigious St. Michael's School in Lüneburg, which played a critical role in exposing him to broader European culture during his two-year stay.
events.fun_version: Bach decided to roll the dice and enroll in St. Michael's School in Lüneburg, a place where his musical talents would flourish! His two-year stay there played a critical role in exposing him to broader European culture, greatly enriching his musical journey.

events.title: Appointment as Court Musician
events.summary: Bach was appointed as a court musician in Weimar after graduating from school, marking the beginning of his professional music career.
events.fun_version: Fresh out of school, Bach strutted into Weimar like he owned the place, snagging a gig as a court musician. Little did they know, they just hired a musical genius… or at least a guy with a serious affinity for wigs and harpsichords! This moment marked the official launch of his professional music career.

events.title: Organist at the New Church
events.summary: Bach became the organist at the New Church in Arnstadt, where he gained a reputation as a notable keyboardist.
events.fun_version: So, Bach landed a gig as the organist at the New Church in Arnstadt. Imagine him rocking the keys while the congregation is just trying to get those hymns right! They probably thought, 'Wow, we hired a keyboard wizard!' As it turns out, he became quite the renowned keyboardist, so mission accomplished!

events.title: Marriage to Maria Barbara Bach
events.summary: Bach married his second cousin, Maria Barbara Bach, shortly after taking up his post in Mühlhausen, leading to a significant chapter in his life.
events.fun_version: Bach decided marrying his second cousin, Maria Barbara Bach, was a good idea! Shortly after accepting a job in Mühlhausen, he dove headfirst into a significant chapter of his life – where he learned that family can be a powerful muse!

events.title: Return to Weimar
events.summary: Bach returned to Weimar as the organist and later became the concertmaster, initiating a prolific period for composition and performance.
events.fun_version: Bach returned to Weimar as the organist and later became the concertmaster, not just to play the organ but to start a musical revolution! It was like he walked in and said, "Why have one job when you can take on the role of concertmaster too? Let's make this place the Disneyland for composers!" This period became incredibly prolific for his composition and performance.

events.title: Death of Maria Barbara Bach
events.summary: Bach's first wife, Maria Barbara, died, which deeply affected him as he had to navigate his personal and professional life thereafter.
events.fun_version: After Maria Barbara's unfortunate passing, Bach was deeply affected as he had to navigate his personal and professional life while trying to keep his career in harmony — talk about a tough duet!

events.title: Marriage to Anna Magdalena Wilcke
events.summary: Bach met and married Anna Magdalena Wilcke, a gifted soprano, marking a new beginning with a family and many children.
events.fun_version: Bach met Anna Magdalena Wilcke, a talented soprano, and it was love at first note! They tied the knot, marking a new beginning that turned their home into a bustling symphony of family and a veritable orchestra of kids!

events.title: Appointment as Thomaskantor
events.summary: Bach was appointed as Thomaskantor in Leipzig, responsible for directing church music and St. Thomas School, which he held for 27 years.
events.fun_version: Bach got a hot gig as the Thomaskantor in Leipzig—basically the head honcho of church music—where he conducted so many hymns and cantatas that they should have given him a gold-plated quill pen! He stuck around for a whopping 27 years!

events.title: Visit to King Frederick II of Prussia
events.summary: Bach visited the court of King Frederick II in Potsdam, where he showcased his improvisational skills and composed The Musical Offering.
events.fun_version: Bach swaggered into King Frederick II's court in Potsdam, ready to show off his improvisational skills like a musical magician, and whipped up The Musical Offering.

events.title: Death
events.summary: Bach passed away after multiple unsuccessful eye surgeries, leading to complications stemming from his deteriorating health.
events.fun_version: Bach had more failed eye surgeries than a cat trying to catch a laser pointer, which unfortunately led to complications stemming from his deteriorating health.
